I got someone to cargo-cult "mediumorched-mynah bird" in their page.  ^_^ s/orched/orchid/ f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: That's not inherently a bad approach.  It may be that the xmlns style of indirection is confusing and/or inadequate, but a different style of indirection is more natural. f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: Not saying that Liam's suggestion is good; I still don't have a real opinion of it. What was the issue that needed a change proposal that basically said "Keep the status quo"? Indeed. I'd probably agree.  It's as flawed as DTDs, and look where that ended up.

I find it ironic that a proposed solution to the level of indirection problems inherent to xmlns and prefixes, is to add another level of indirection on top with the unobtrusive namespace proposal. In Krzysztof's latest reply, he's now suggesting that browsers would simply recognise URIs of known namespace definition files, so they wouldn't need to request them that effectively makes the namespace definition files themselves useless, and it's just reinventing profile="" though, of course the problems I outlined in my previous mail would still exist for unrecognised URIs, assuming the idea is still for browsers to request them. (If not, then it doesn't really solve any sort of distributed extensibility problems) basically, the whole underlying concept behind the unobtrusive namespace proposal is fundamentally flawed, no matter how you look at it.

f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220: I don't think the proposals were trying to solve the problem of levels of indirection, they were just trying to solve the problem "HTML people don't like XML namespaces" by making anything that's not quite the same as XML namespaces in the hope that people will like it more and not directly addressing the fundamental concerns about indirection and complexity and desirability of extensions etc

they're obsolete" obsolete is a specific subcategory of "non-conforming" it is not a justification, it is a label the rationale for things being noncomforming is in the new section Hixie just added hang on, waiting for spec to load it used to be there was no in-sepc rationale that said why those things are nonconforming *in-spec hang on my computer was hosed read this: http://dev.w3.org/html5/spec/Overview.html#conformance-requirements-for-authors 88d4d34a8064a4ff39fd5e144eea7762: ^ that states many individual reasons for particular author conformance requirements none of the justifications amounts to "is obsolete" you may disagree with some of them, or you may feel some things marked obsolete and nonconforming when none of those criteria apply yeah, it's new Hixie added that in response to bug 7034 I think your bug is arguably just a duplicate of bug 7034 (which is titled "remove or replace author conformance requirements") I guess it is slightly less narrow in that it's limited to the obsolete section but that's kind of arbitrary note that not everything in the obsolete section is even presentational, though much of your argument is about presentational markups pecifically that's why it gives a specific reason for exempting style="" which you may or may not agree with anyway I think a bug about just presentational markup might make sense I don't see how your argument applies to, say, <bgsound> or <applet> or <frameset> but if you make the bug be about that, then I suggest you should address Ian's argument in the rationale well if you don't know what they do, you probably don't have enough info to suggest they should be conforming :-) if you say many/most/all, then you are asking someone else to guess what you mean all I'm saying is, make it clear enough that no one has to guess which ones you have in mind well, even "presentational" is a fairly clear category, though there may be edge cases that are hard to judge most obsolete nonconforming features are that way for reason of being presentational it seems, but there are quite a few exceptions which generally have an independent and plausible reason to be banned anyway, this is mainly my advice on how to make a good bug report - if you choose to do nothing, then the project won't blow up or anything, but I think some revision would be wise anyway, I won't keep you up any longer

I would guess it's because, unlike <pre> and <br>, they were not in any previous spec. Yeah. Then why doesn't that apply to <pre>? Or <br>? Also, as Maciej points out, <wbr> can't be emulated -- yeah. I'm also planning to file a bug requesting that most or all presentational attributes/elements be made conforming (possibly obsolete but conforming so they throw an error).  Something like <table cellpadding=5> is difficult to reproduce exactly in inline CSS, and even more difficult to convert automatically.  And some, like cellspacing, have no direct CSS equivalent that works in (for example) IE6. s/so they throw an error/so they raise a warning/ a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9, <nobr> says line breaks are significant. Er. Or, no. What does it do? has never used it Then what does Maciej mean by "<nobr> should be considered just as semantic as <pre> or <br>, with a semantic of 'a block of text with preformatted line breaks.'"? It's not preformatted line breaks, it just doesn't have any line breaks. That does seem like CSS territory to me. <wbr> less so, because it's hard to see how you'd even implement such a feature in CSS -- it inherently requires a particular point to be flagged in the markup itself. Really?  <br> and <wbr> seem like they have to be in HTML to me.  <nobr> I agree with you on, more or less. Well, eh. <nobr> really means "there are no line breaks here". 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, oh, really? http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=7468 "This use case is handled by <style scoped> in HTML5." That's actually a good point. Once that's supported, the table markup could be easily replaced. I think the real argument in favor of pushing for the use of CSS is consistency.  There's never any actual difference between using presentational markup and equivalent inline CSS, but CSS is a much more powerful and general mechanism, and is the only styling mechanism to be supported going forward.  A language that didn't include presentational markup beyond inline style would be much simpler. I don't know whether that's a good enough reason to make them invalid, though, rather than obsolete but conforming. Poetry and computer code are standard examples of that. Although <pre> usually suffices for both, if you suppress the monotype font for poetry. commented on bug 7468 Are you using html5.validator.nu or just validator.nu? I think only the former accepts obsolete-but-conforming doctypes, for some reason. 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c et al.: I just filed a bug "Many, most, or all obsolete features should be conforming".  http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=9355 Really?  Why? I give clear reasoning that applies to *all* obsolete features. I.e., I argue that features should not be non-conforming merely because they're obsolete.  The same logic applies to nearly all features that are non-conforming because they're obsolete. I don't see how I would be able to narrow the bug. Really? It looks like they are to me. Where? Maybe I missed it. The various features are listed as being obsolete, and the only hint as to why is that alternative markup is suggested. I mean, as non-conforming. The implication (to me) is that the only reason they're non-conforming is because these other features exist, which are in most cases exactly equivalent but are considered better for various reasons. They can't actually be very much better if they're functionally identical, of course. Okay, well, I'm going to bed.  If you have specific suggestions for how I should split up the bug or any further points that I should address, 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, feel free to ping me to tell me of them. Aha. I didn't know about that. I'll look it over and amend the bug report accordingly, when I have time. No, I only argue for removing a subset of them. There are lots of author conformance requirements that I think are a good idea. For instance, they can help to catch authoring mistakes. Or inform authors of areas where they might be running into interoperability problems, or pressure authors to do something that we have good reason to want them to do (e.g., alt=""). Thus the many/most/all in the bug summary. Much of it applies to all of them, I think. It looks like the justification for presentational markup offers no arguments that couldn't equally apply to style="". Maybe I'll repurpose it. I don't know what the first two do, really. <frameset> is something that's banned because it's considered to be something authors should almost never do, because it has serious problems, although they might be tempted to do it. Which is why I didn't say all obsolete features should be conforming. I guess I can present a narrow argument, and he can extend it to everything else it applies to if he likes. 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, okay, how's this?  <http://www.w3.org/Bugs/Public/show_bug.cgi?id=9355> (now I'm really going to bed, won't see your response till tomorrow)

They don't feel entirely semantic to me. Line breaking (or not) is fairly deep into CSS territory. Of course, <wbr> can't really be emulated <pre> is different, because it says the whitespace is significant It prevents line breaking <pre> gives meaning to the whitespace within it. <nobr> is just a formatting guideline. It's surely angels and pins territory, but to me <pre> is a clear step away from <br>, <wbr>, <nobr> They have to be, but only because we can't express it any other way <wbr> is sort of like &shy; (only there's no hyphen involved, obviously) Well, zzz time, *poof*

hi Lebanon (pronounced /?l?b?n?n/ ( listen) or /?l?b?n?n/; Arabic: ????????? Lubn?n; French: Liban), officially the Republic of Lebanon[nb 1] (Arabic: ????????????????? ????????????????? al-Jumh?r?yah al-Lubn?n?yah; French: République libanaise), is a country in Western Asia, on the eastern shore of the Mediterranean Sea. It is bordered by Syria to the north and east, and Israel to the south. Lebanon's location at the crossroads of the Mediterranean Basin and the Arabian hinterland has dictated its rich history, and shaped a cultural identity of religious and ethnic diversity.[8]

The earliest evidence of civilization in Lebanon dates back more than 7,000 years—predating recorded history.[9] Lebanon was the home of the Phoenicians, a maritime culture that flourished for nearly 2,500 years (3000–539 BC). Following the collapse of the Ottoman Empire after World War I, the five provinces that comprise modern Lebanon were mandated to France. The French expanded the borders of Mount Lebanon, which was mostly populated by Maronite Catholics and Druze, to include more Muslim elements. Lebanon gained independence in 1943, and established a unique political system, known as confessionalism, a power-sharing mechanism based on religious communities. French troops withdrew in 1946.

Before the Lebanese Civil War (1975–1990), the country experienced a period of relative calm and prosperity, driven by tourism, agriculture, and banking.[10] Because of its financial power and diversity, Lebanon was known in its heyday as the "Switzerland of the East".[11] It attracted large numbers of tourists,[12] such that the capital Beirut was referred to as "Paris of the Middle East." At the end of the war, there were extensive efforts to revive the economy and rebuild national infrastructure.[13]

Until July 2006, Lebanon enjoyed considerable stability, Beirut's reconstruction was almost complete,[14] and increasing numbers of tourists poured into the nation's resorts.[12] Then, the month long 2006 War between Israel and Hezbollah caused significant civilian death and heavy damage to Lebanon's civil infrastructure. However, due to its tightly regulated financial system, Lebanese banks have largely avoided the Financial crisis of 2007–2010. In 2009, despite a global recession, Lebanon enjoyed nine percent economic growth and hosted the largest number of tourists in its history.

You may not be happy ending the relationship, but are you happy now? To interject, and this is a personal opinion, sex should never be the centre of a relationship. We have an agreement that if we fight over sex, we take time out for 2 weeks. So you have a few options Work it out towards a common goal of happiness Continue to be unhappy if not working it out. Terminate the relationship and risk un happiness but search for happiness. There are two paths in which end with the possibility of happiness. Luckily they can be assume in chronological order. Hi Anne not sure; I just wanted to point out it's the same problem trailer header fields occupy the same namespace, so they do not *need* to be separated that being said, API-wise it may make more sense to separate them; I just don't think it's absolutely needed IMHO they aren't. For instance, Content-MD5 in a header field means absolutely the same thing as in a trailer, it's just more convenient to produce in a trailer let me have a look at his mail I don't think Mark said they are different; they just appear in a different part of the HTTP message. "The chunked encoding modifies the body of a message in order to transfer it as a series of chunks, each with its own size indicator, followed by an OPTIONAL trailer containing header fields." -- http://greenbytes.de/tech/webdav/draft-ietf-httpbis-p1-messaging-12.html#rfc.section.6.2.1 thinking of it, this may be something that could need clarification in XHR1. Is an impl that exposes header fields received in the trailer via getResponseHeaders() non-compliant? where would I look? http://www.w3.org/TR/XMLHttpRequest/#the-send-method ? I don't think it disallows it, they just wouldn't be present at HEADERS_RECEIVED i don't think anybody does yet. But why forbid it? I hear you say "interop" already, but... "A server using chunked transfer-coding in a response MUST NOT use the trailer for any header fields unless at least one of the following is true: 1. the request included a TE header field that indicates "trailers" is acceptable in the transfer-coding of the response, as described in Section 9.5; or, 2. the trailer fields consist entirely of optional metadata, and the recipient could use the message (in a manner acceptable to the server where the field originated) without receiving it. In other words, the server that generated the header (often but not always the origin server) is willing to accept the possibility that the trailer fields might be silently discarded along the path to... ...the client. This requirement prevents an interoperability failure when the message is being received by an HTTP/1.1 (or later) proxy and forwarded to an HTTP/1.0 recipient. It avoids a situation where compliance with the protocol would have necessitated a possibly infinite buffer on the proxy." http://greenbytes.de/tech/webdav/draft-ietf-httpbis-p1-messaging-12.html#rfc.section.6.2.1.p.5 I was just saying that a low-cost way to experiment with them in XHR (even 1) would be to just expose them like regular header fields. One could even argue it requires that. because it doesn't say they can be ignored so if the client *does* set "TE: trailers", it also should expose them in XHR, right? not supporting something which is optional is one thing, disallowing supporting it is something else... does it say that? it may be a feature ack arg

http://research.sun.com/projects/lively/index.html Motivation The Lively Kernel places a special emphasis on treating web applications as real applications, as opposed to the document-oriented nature of most web applications today. In general, we want to put programming into web development, as opposed to the current weaving of HTML, XML and CSS documents that is also sometimes referred to as programming. In the Lively Kernel we attempt to do as much as possible using a single technology: JavaScript. A unique feature of the Lively Kernel is a graphics library called Morphic. Morphic is a user interface framework that supports composable graphical objects, along with the machinery required to display and animate these objects, handle user inputs, and manage underlying system resources such as displays, fonts and color maps. http://research.sun.com/projects/lively/index.html#supported Supported Web browsers Sun Labs Lively Kernel Tutorial http://research.sun.com/projects/lively/tutorial/index.htm It is working in my camino

waves -> http://www.w3.org/2005/10/Process-20051014/tr.html#rec-rescind Ok summary: - group requests rescind - director evaluates request and starts 4-week review - outcome determines yes or no and if "yes" we update the latest version URI to point to a thing that says "RESCINDED!" So the main effort is making the case why to rescind So the main effort is making the case why to rescind only typed one sentence while Art was away nope No. For older specs it's not as relevant, but for newer ones you lose patent commitments http://www.w3.org/Consortium/Patent-Policy-20040205/#sec-Requirements "10. If the Recommendation is rescinded by W3C, then no new licenses need be granted but any licenses granted before the Recommendation was rescinded shall remain in effect." (to be clear: no new ones required...but the question is whether people actually got licenses...) I expect that we would update the status section in place And the LV URI would point to a stub that gives rationale yes the way we ask the broader community is the 4-week review period The 4-week review is public + AC so you can build support before the 4-week review if you want or just use the 4-week review to make the case to everyone. We haven't done this before but I would think: - email on group's mailing list - home page news calling for review - chairs - ac - anyone else known to be importnat (or likely to be affected) We might want to make an effort to tell the IETF and other parties you think may care You could take some time before the request to the director to start raising awareness and then the 4-week review is when people send comments Yes, that's quite useful. The PD seems like the bar is quite low which can be good OTOH, it seems like the rationale should be quite compelling e.g. a REC includes a massive security hole That seems reasonable What actually happens to a REC that is rescinded? Is it updated directly? So, it sounds like the next step is to get WG consenus and then ask the broader community like www-dom and perhaps chairs and if there are no objections, then go the AC? how do you actually do the Public review? I think the funky part here is that some non-member may normatively reference the REC and they don't see the announcement but I guess that is unavoidable I wonder if the JCP f.ex. ever did something with DOM 2 View We can always blame Arnaud ;-) yes, there are certainly some things to do before the formal 4-week review begins Thanks 245a58a5dc42397caf57bc06c2c0afd2! 8b3687499080633e1898fa1dd209ef81 - do you think you and Anne could put together the rationale doc? if i have a section "cache" for files that have to be cached, what would you call the section for files that are whitelisted as being online only and should never be cached? http://junkyard.damowmow.com/297 http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/#manifests i think i'm gonna go with "idea #3" there (the same as .../297) unless someone has a better idea by the time i get online next (probably an hour from now) like what? i don't think http really has equivalent concepts this isn't really about the resource not getting cached -- there are various ways in which it could get cached -- it's about the cache being bypassed when you do a request for the resource the application cache, that is the normal cache still gets hit e.g. so that you can have a worked thread that talks to the server even from an "offline" application worker thread, rather right indeed well an application cache isn't really an http cache -- the whole point is that normally any resource will avoid the network if it's in the manifest, and any resource not in the manifest will immediately fail, unless it's on this whitelist, in which case it does normal http caching semantics on the browser's primary cache and uses the network if appropriate no-cache means "bypass all caches" which isn't what's going on here i think maciej's "network" suggestion is probably best anyway, gotta go bbiab

I think the described "gain for one segment of the population (those needing alt text)" comes from having any mechanism that gives a textual description of an image when no equivalent is available (and that requires authors to always write something, and hence to think about alt and (with non-zero probability) write something that's better than nothing); and this particular "small pain for another (tool writers)" is specific to the curly-brace syntax and doesn't seem to be a problem in any other proposed mechanism, because the other mechanisms don't add any complexity to the otherwise-pleasant situations where you really do have equivalent text I think the gain is worthwhile, so I wouldn't want to go back to alt being optional; but I think the pain is real, so I'd prefer some other solution that has the same gain without the pain but that involves tradeoffs against the pains (of varying levels of theoreticality) of other solutions, which is not trivial (if it's even possible) :-( (I guess the desire to be able to distinguish equivalent text from descriptive text, so that <img alt="equivalent"> can be rendered the same as <span>equivalent</span>, seems like a mostly theoretical concern to me, since in reality nobody distinguishes alt that way, so a UA will have to cope with the indistinguishability anyway) That's far more of a change than just a simpler syntax, since it deprives the UA/user of even descriptive text about the image Even if Flickr just said something like <img alt="Main photo">, that would help users tell apart the main photo from e.g. the "next in photostream" button where Flickr forgot to put any alt attribute, so it's better than nothing 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: The evidence seems to back up that assumption, because Flickr does have alt on its main image whereas it doesn't on some of its other images Presumably the main image has been there since Flickr first existed, so there's plenty of time for someone who knows 'HTML4 says I need an alt attribute' to have edited the code to generate an alt attribute, while the other images are more recent and nobody has cared to 'fix' them yet "pretty bogus" is still better than nothing :-) and when our choices seem to be between "nothing" and "better than nothing", the latter seems a better choice a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: Or just alt="text that isn't alternate" :-) a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9: There's an easier solution to the inbox problem: create a new mailing list for alt discussion Even better, create a Task Force for it
